sentences: In 1937, she wrote a ballet Cracked Ice, for the Boston Skating Club.
In 1952 she married Joseph R. Coolidge, a freelance writer from Boston.
She wrote her only film score for The Silken Affair, starring David Niven, in 1956.
In 1963 and 1965, she was invited to Vienna, Budapest, Warsaw and Moscow for performances of her works, also sometimes appearing as piano soloist.
Rhapsody for Harp and Orchestra was written in 1965.
In 1967 her works were played in Tokyo in a concert of American music, and she was received by Emperor Hirohito's brother, Prince Mikasa.
In 1969 Peggy Stuart Coolidge wrote Spirituals in Sunshine and Shadow, an orchestral work inspired by African-American blues and spirituals.
In 1970 she wrote Pioneer Dances, inspired by the 19th century settlers of America.
In 1970 also, at Khachaturian's instigation, she became the first American composer to have a concert devoted entirely to her works presented in the Soviet Union.
In 1971, at the request of the World Wildlife Fund, she composed a three-minute theme to complement the fund's visual symbol of a giant panda on a green field.
In 1975, the Westphalian Symphony Orchestra conducted by Siegfried Landau recorded one of the first LPs ever devoted to the works of a single American female composer.
American Mosaic was written in 1978 on a commission by the American Wind Symphony.

sentences: Peggy Stuart Coolidge (19 July 1913 – 7 May 1981) was an American composer and conductor.
Her orchestral scores Night Froth, The Island (sinfonietta), Smoke Drift and Twilight City (piano and orchestra) were all premiered by the Boston Pops.
She founded the Junior League Orchestra in Boston and conducted it for seven years.
A ballet An Evening in New York was written on her return to the United States.
In 1970 she wrote Pioneer Dances, inspired by the 19th century settlers of America.
This was the only American work played at a 1975 Carnegie Hall concert to commemorate the 150th anniversary of Norwegian immigration to the United States.
That year also saw New England Autumn, a two-movement suite for chamber orchestra.
The works were the Rhapsody for Harp and Orchestra (with soloist Aristid von Würtzler), New England Autumn, Pioneer Dances, and Spirituals in Sunshine and Shadow.
